The paper deals with computing Shapley values for geometric objects (points) in a set, specifically in 3-D. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper presents a new data structure for a variant of the dynamic convolution problem, which falls under the data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The Shapley value is a concept from game theory, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the game theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The paper also involves computing mean width and mean volume, which are related to computational geometry and optimization, respectively, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and numerical analysis (cs.NA) sub-categories.
